This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) category as it presents an end-to-end deep architecture for stereo matching that produces high-quality, edge-preserved, quantization-free disparity maps. The paper also uses a Siamese network to extract features from the left and right image, which is a common technique in computer vision. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of color input as a guide for producing high-quality edge-aware output, which is another common technique in computer vision. 

The paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) category as it uses a deep learning approach to achieve real-time stereo matching. 

The paper may belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) category as it presents a novel approach to stereo matching that achieves sub-pixel matching precision and hierarchical refinement. 

The paper may belong to the robotics (cs.RO) category as stereo matching is an important task in robotics for depth perception and obstacle avoidance. 

Finally, the paper may belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) category as it discusses the production of high-quality disparity maps, which are commonly used in multimedia applications such as virtual reality and augmented reality.
